      <block class="full_text">
        <p>LEAD: To the Editor:</p>
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Regret about our slow economic growth continues to fill the pages of The Times - most recently, ''When the World's Growth Slows,'' by Steven Greenhouse (Dec. 27). Yet the rest of the paper is filled with the horrible consequences of growth: the ozone depletion, the loss of tropical rain forests, the towers to be built on the Coliseum site at Columbus Circle.</p>
        <p>Mr. Greenhouse notes that lack of growth means that ''for many people real earnings will remain basically unchanged throughout their lifetimes.''</p>
        <p>Yes, too bad, but we must begin to accept limits to the numbers of televisions, plastic cups, hairspray cans and other detritus of civilization, to save our planet earth.</p>
        <p>Please have your writers address the downside of growth in the same breath as they extoll it. CHALMERS HARDENBERGH  Institute for Defense and Disarmament Studies  Brookline, Mass., Dec. 27</p>
      </block>
